[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-alaska] Wade on May 2, 2022, Alaska saw abortion rights protests in Anchorage, Fairbanks, and Haines.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-alaska] David Eastman (R-Wasilla) was censured by the Alaska Legislature in 2017 after he claimed that women used Medicaid support for abortion as a "free trip to the city".
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-alaska] A small counter-protest was organized by anti-abortion rights activists at the Alaska Capitol in Juneau in May 2019, in support of proposed restrictions on women's ability to access legal abortions in the state.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-american-samoa] In 2016, the Zika virus hit American Samoa particularly hard, despite efforts to prevent its spread, with 21 pregnant women known to have contracted the virus in a population of 55,000 people.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-american-samoa] Pregnant women across American Samoa were given condoms when seeking prenatal care at four clinics and one hospital starting in 2015 and continuing to 2016.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-american-samoa] This was facilitated in part by all prenatal care in American Samoa being subsidized by the government beginning in the summer of 2015, which also increased women seeking prenatal care as they previously waited until the third-trimester to seek care.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-american-samoa] A September 20, 1985 directive from the American Samoa Attorney General stated that elective abortions are unconstitutional and that no such procedures can occur at public hospitals.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-american-samoa] Legal code section 46.3904, which passed in 1986, said that no physician or hospital employee can be compelled to participate in an abortion procedure if doing so goes against their conscience, and that such refusals are immune to criminal, administrative or disciplinary action.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-american-samoa] Legal code sections passed in 1986 declared that the only persons who can perform a legal abortion in American Samoa are licensed American Samoan physicians.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-american-samoa] As of 1998, legal code sections 46.3902 and 46.3903, which were adopted in 1986, made any attempt to terminate a pregnancy except in the case of saving the physical or mental health of the mother a crime.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-american-samoa] As of 2014, abortion medications like mifepristone were not available in American Samoa, because the government does not permit Title X funding to be used for abortions.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-american-samoa] The morning after pill was available because it prevented conception and was not legally considered an abortifacient.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] In January 2023, the South Carolina Supreme Court had struck down a similar existing law as violating the state's privacy clause under Article 1, Section 10 of the South Carolina Constitution.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] Passed in 2021, that law had criminalized abortion once embryonic cardiac activity is detectable, which is around five or six weeks after the first day of the woman's last menstrual period.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] In 2024, South Carolina lawmakers introduced a bill that would define abortion as "prenatal homicide"; and make abortion patients eligible for the death penalty.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] The number of abortion clinics in South Carolina has fluctuated over the years, with fifteen in 1982, eighteen in 1992 and three in 2014.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] In 2022, when a political campaign polled South Carolina adults, it found that 53% support "a woman’s right to choose to have a safe and legal abortion" while 37% do not.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] South Carolinian women have a long history of traveling outside the state to seek legal abortions.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] Critics of efforts by state lawmakers to restrict abortion access say it results in South Carolinian women needing to spend more money and travel greater distances for the procedure.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] On June 2, 2023, 22-year old Amari Marsh, who was attending South Carolina State University, was arrested and improperly charged with homicide after experiencing a miscarriage that March.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] She spent 22 days in jail and was released to house arrest before her case was cleared by a grand jury.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] On July 3, 2025, a 31-year old woman was arrested in Florence County, South Carolina after experiencing a miscarriage and disposing of the fetal remains in the trash.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] If convicted, she faces up to 10 years in prison.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] By the end of the 1800s, all states in the Union except Louisiana had therapeutic exceptions in their legislative bans on abortions.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] In the 19th century, bans by state legislatures on abortion were about protecting the life of the mother given the number of deaths caused by abortions; state governments saw themselves as looking out for the lives of their citizens.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] By 1950, the state legislature would pass a law that stated that a woman who had an abortion or actively sought to have an abortion regardless of whether she went through with it was guilty of a criminal offense.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] In 2013, state Targeted Regulation of Abortion Providers (TRAP) law applied to medication induced abortions and private doctor offices in addition to abortion clinics.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] Governor Nikki Haley signed legislation that brought into effect a 20-week abortion ban in 2016.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] At a ceremonial signing ceremony for the cameras, she was surrounded by children with disabilities.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] Republican Representative Greg Delleney was the lead sponsor of South Carolina's law requiring that women view an ultrasound of a fetus before being allowed to have an abortion.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] He said the ultrasound would enable the woman to "determine for herself whether she is carrying an unborn child deserving of protection or whether it's just an inconvenient, unnecessary part of her body." Rep.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] McCravy III prefiled HB 3020 in the South Carolina House of Representatives in December 2018.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] The bill, entitled the "Fetal Heartbeat Protection from Abortion Act", was introduced on January 8, 2018, and referred to the House Judiciary Committee.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] Previous attempts to pass "fetal heartbeat" bills in the South Carolina General Assembly failed.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] The state legislature was one of ten states nationwide that tried to pass similar legislation that year.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] House of Representatives passed a "fetal heartbeat" bill.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] The measure passed after five hours of debate.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] In February 2021, South Carolina passed a law which would outlaw almost all abortions in that state after embryonic cardiac-cell activity is detected; however, that law was temporarily blocked by a judge in March 2021.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] In September 2022, the South Carolina Legislature failed in an attempt to ban abortion at fertilization due to objections from female legislators for being too strict.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] The legislature then failed to make stricter the state's existing 6-week abortion ban due to objections from the caucus that the proposed new law wasn't strict enough.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] Shane Massey, Josh Kimbrell, and Brian Adams (politician) authored Bill 474, the "Fetal Heartbeat and Protection from Abortion" Act, which outlaws almost all abortions in the state after embryonic cardiac-cell activity is detected.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] South Carolina entered it into law on May 25, 2023, despite its similarity to 2021's fetal heartbeat law the state Supreme Court struck down.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] The law generally banned abortion once there is "cardiac activity, or the steady and repetitive rhythmic contraction of the fetal heart, within the gestational sac".
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] The supposed "cardiac activity" is not a heartbeat, instead being embryonic electrical activity, which can be detected from around six weeks from the woman's last menstrual period.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] Many women do not yet know that they are pregnant at six weeks since the woman's last menstrual period.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] In 2023, Republican Representative Rob Harris authored the South Carolina Prenatal Equal Protection Act of 2023, which would make women who had abortions eligible for the death penalty.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] The bill attracted 21 Republican co-sponsors.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] The bill would define fertilized eggs as human beings and offers no exception for pregnant individuals seeking abortion due to sexual assault, incest, or poor fetal health.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] In April 2023, 5 State Senators filibustered an almost total abortion ban in a bipartisan group.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] (However, the Supreme Court overturned *Roe v.
