[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] 215 (2022) later in 2022.) The US Supreme Court heard *Ferguson v.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] On appeal, the Fourth Circuit had affirmed, but on the ground that the searches were justified as a matter of law by special non-law-enforcement needs.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] The Supreme Court had a 6–3 ruling in the case, which was about a South Carolina public hospital policy requiring all pregnant women to be drug tested.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] The Supreme Court ruled that the US Constitution's Fourth Amendment protected women against unreasonable search and seizures, which mandatory drug testing was.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] The US Supreme Court reasoned that the interest in curtailing pregnancy complications and reducing the medical costs associated with maternal cocaine use outweighed what it characterized as a "minimal intrusion" on the women's privacy.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] The Supreme Court then agreed to hear the case.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] Justice Kennedy pointed out that all searches, by definition, would uncover evidence of crime, and this says nothing about the "special needs" the search might serve.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] In *Planned Parenthood South Atlantic, et al. v.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] State of South Carolina, et al.*, the South Carolina Supreme Court struck down the state's six-week abortion ban from 2021 and ruled that the state constitution's privacy clause included an implicit right to abortion.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] A day after South Carolina's 2023 abortion law was implemented, Circuit Court Judge Clifton Newman issued a temporary restraining order that prevents the law from being enforced until the state supreme court can make a ruling on the law's constitutionality.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] In August 2023, the South Carolina Supreme Court ruled that the state's 2023 law, banning most abortions after cardiac activity is detected, is constitutional.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] In June 2025, the US Supreme Court ruled that a South Carolina woman and Planned Parenthood lack legal standing to challenge the state’s decision to exclude Planned Parenthood from its Medicaid program due to its abortion services.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] Between 1982 and 1992, the number of abortion clinics in the state increased by three, going from fifteen in 1982 to eighteen in 1992.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] In 2014, there were three abortion clinics in the state.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] In 2014, 93% of the counties in the state did not have an abortion clinic.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] That year, 71% of women in the state aged 15–44 lived in a county without an abortion clinic.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] In 2017, there were two Planned Parenthood clinics, one of which offered abortion services, in a state with a population of 1,112,199 women aged 15–49.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] In 2018, there were three licensed abortion clinics in the state.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] They were in Charleston, Columbia and Greenville.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] The Charleston clinic was a Planned Parenthood clinic in West Ashley.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] In the period between 1972 and 1974, the state had an illegal abortion mortality rate per million women aged 15–44 of between 0.1 and 0.9.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] In 1990, 411,000 women in the state faced the risk of an unintended pregnancy.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] There were around 5,600 women in South Carolina in 1995 who left the state to get an abortion.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] There were around 8,801 abortions performed in South Carolina in 1998.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] In 2010, the state had nine publicly funded abortions, of which all were federally funded and none were state funded.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] In 2013, among white women aged 15–19, there were 660 abortions, 620 abortions for black women aged 15–19, 60 abortions for Hispanic women aged 15–19, and 40 abortions for women of all other races.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] In 2014, 42% of adults said in a poll by the Pew Research Center that abortion should be legal in all or most cases.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] Around 5,600 women in South Carolina in 2015 left the state to get an abortion.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] This number was one of the highest in the United States.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] Only 5.9% of abortions performed in the state involved out-of-state residents in 2015.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] This contrasted with neighboring Georgia, where 14.5% of all abortions that year were for out-of-state residents, and neighboring North Carolina, where 7.5% of all abortions were for out-of-state residents.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] In 2017, nearly 11,000 South Carolina residents had abortions, but more than half of those were performed out of state.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] That year, South Carolina had an infant mortality rate of 6.5 deaths per 1,000 live births.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] Protesters participated in marches supporting abortion rights as part of a Stop the Bans movement in May 2019.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] Wade on June 24, 2022, an abortion rights protest was held on June 25 in Greenville.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] In Columbia, South Carolina on May 15, 2023, a group of abortion rights protesters rallied at the South Carolina statehouse in opposition to the state's 6-week abortion ban.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] The bill failed to advance out of subcommittee, following statewide and nationwide backlash.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] Between 1998 and 2017, the number of abortions that took place on a yearly basis in the state dropped by 5,112.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] According to anti-abortion rights group South Carolina Citizens for Life this drop meant that harsh anti-abortion measures in the state worked.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] They were saying rape was the fault of the woman.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] They called these women baby killers and murderers.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] That language is so degrading toward women, particularly victims of rape or incest.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] And I said to myself I'm not going to put up with that bull----.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] On February 23, 2023, anti-abortion protesters physically clashed with abortion rights protesters outside of a clinic in Greenville, South Carolina.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] On November 14, 2025, one person was injured during a shooting outside of a Planned Parenthood in Columbia, South Carolina.
[src:abortion-in-south-carolina/abortion-in-south-carolina] Mark Baumgartner, the founder of anti-abortion group "A Moment Of Hope", was arrested and charged with assault and battery of a high and aggravated nature and possession of a weapon during a violent crime.
